parameters: \>What \c[4]Move Route Plugins\c[0] would you like to learn about?\<
<WordWrap>\c[4]RPG Maker MV\c[0] gives us a lot of various commands to use for our Move Routes.
<WordWrap>However, it still imposes a lot of limitations on the system for what else could still be potentially useful for move route commands.
<WordWrap>This plugin will provide additional methods to construct move routes for your events and allow you to streamline the move route creation process.
<WordWrap>This plugin adds extra simplified move routes for your events with the main intention of creating specific behaviors in movement patterns.
<WordWrap>The patterns include the option to hug a side of the wall and move along that, moving a single direction until coming to a stop, relative opacity adjusting, and index shifting.

<Wordwrap>Sometimes, we'd like a little bit more control over the kinds of things that occur during certain aspects of our RPG Maker projects. What could have been easily done through common events is made more difficult because there are no proper triggers to activate those common events. This plugin enables certain triggers to occur from loading a game, winning a battle, escaping a battle, and more.

<Wordwrap>It's not surprising for streamlined games nowadays to have their own help manuals included with the game or accessible within the game. RPG Maker MV doesn't provide anything like that by default, unfortunately. However, using this plugin, you can create ways to access the helpfile from within your game through either the F1 key or an in-game menu.

<Wordwrap>In RPG Maker MV, you can only assign one skill type per skill. This means that each skill can only appear under one skill type library when scrolling through a skill list. Yet, in traditional RPG's, we sometimes see skills that can exist in multiple skill types. A "Cure" spell might appear in both "White Magic" and "Red Magic" at the same time. This plugin enables the possibility to give skills multiple skill types.

<Wordwrap>This plugin gives your player and/or events footsteps when they walk onto tiles. These footsteps made by players and/or events can have different sounds based on regions, tilesets, and/or terrain tags. If footsteps are enabled for events, they can have distance based volumes and pitches to immerse the player further.
